<h3>1. Central Appetite Suppression</h3>

<p>GLP-1 receptors are expressed in the hypothalamus and brainstem, regions critical for appetite regulation. Semaglutide crosses the blood-brain barrier and acts on these receptors to reduce hunger and increase satiety.</p>

<p>Neuroimaging studies show that semaglutide dampens neural responses to food cues in reward-associated brain regions, reducing cravings and the hedonic drive to eat (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33269530/">Friedrichsen et al., 2021</a>).</p>

<h3>2. Delayed Gastric Emptying</h3>

<p>Semaglutide slows the rate at which food leaves the stomach, prolonging feelings of fullness after meals. This effect is most prominent during the early weeks of treatment.</p>

<p>It partially attenuates over time, though appetite suppression persists through central mechanisms.</p>

<h3>3. Reduced Energy Intake</h3>

<p>In controlled feeding studies, participants on semaglutide consumed approximately <strong>24&ndash;35% fewer calories</strong> compared to placebo. Reductions in fat and ultra-processed food intake were especially notable.</p>

<p>Participants reported less hunger, fewer cravings, and greater control over eating (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28371441/">Blundell et al., 2017</a>).</p>

<h3>4. Metabolic Effects</h3>

<p>Some evidence suggests semaglutide may modestly improve energy expenditure relative to the degree of weight lost. It partially attenuates the metabolic adaptation that normally accompanies caloric restriction, though this remains an area of active research.</p>

<p>It also improves insulin sensitivity, reduces hepatic fat, and favorably modifies lipid profiles. These effects are partly weight-dependent and partly direct.</p>

<!-- ========== STEP TRIALS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>The STEP Trials: What the Clinical Data Shows</h2>

<p>The <strong>Semaglutide Treatment Effect in People with obesity (STEP)</strong> trial program is the largest body of evidence supporting semaglutide for weight management. These were randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trials involving thousands of participants.</p>

<div class="cd ct">
  <div class="tg">Landmark Trial</div>
  <h3>STEP 1: Semaglutide in Adults Without Diabetes</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:12px;"><strong>Population:</strong> 1,961 adults with BMI of 30 or higher (or 27+ with comorbidity), without diabetes. <strong>Duration:</strong> 68 weeks. <strong>Design:</strong> Semaglutide 2.4 mg weekly + lifestyle intervention vs. placebo + lifestyle intervention.</p>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Results:</strong> Mean weight loss of <strong>14.9%</strong> with semaglutide vs. <strong>2.4%</strong> with placebo. 86.4% of participants lost 5% or more of body weight; 69.1% lost 10% or more; 50.5% lost 15% or more (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33567185/">Wilding et al., 2021</a>).</p>
</div>

<h3>STEP Trial Results Summary</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Trial</th><th>Population</th><th>Duration</th><th>Semaglutide Result</th><th>Placebo</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>STEP 1</strong></td><td>Non-diabetic, BMI 30+</td><td>68 wk</td><td class="g">-14.9% body weight</td><td>-2.4%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>STEP 2</strong></td><td>T2D, BMI 27+</td><td>68 wk</td><td class="g">-9.6% body weight</td><td>-3.4%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>STEP 3</strong></td><td>Non-diabetic + IBT</td><td>68 wk</td><td class="g">-16.0% body weight</td><td>-5.7%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>STEP 4</strong></td><td>Withdrawal study</td><td>68 wk</td><td class="g">-7.9% additional</td><td class="r">+6.9% regain</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>STEP 5</strong></td><td>2-year follow-up</td><td>104 wk</td><td class="g">-15.2% body weight</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>STEP 2 showed lower weight loss than STEP 1, which is consistent with the known blunting effect of diabetes and insulin resistance on GLP-1-mediated weight loss (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33667417/">Davies et al., 2021</a>).</p>

<p>STEP 3 combined semaglutide with intensive behavioral therapy (30 sessions), suggesting additive effects of pharmacotherapy and structured behavioral support (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33625476/">Wadden et al., 2021</a>).</p>

<div class="d-r">
  <div class="s">Critical Finding: Weight Regain</div>
  <p>STEP 4 clearly demonstrated that semaglutide-induced weight loss requires ongoing treatment. Those who switched to placebo regained an average of 6.9% of body weight within one year. Stopping leads to significant regain (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33625477/">Rubino et al., 2021</a>).</p>
</div>

<p>STEP 5 showed weight loss of <strong>15.2%</strong> at 2 years, demonstrating durability with continued treatment (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36216945/">Garvey et al., 2022</a>).</p>

<h3>SELECT Trial: Cardiovascular Outcomes</h3>

<div class="cd cb">
  <div class="tg">Cardiovascular Landmark</div>
  <h3>SELECT: First Anti-Obesity Drug to Show CV Benefit</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;">The SELECT trial enrolled 17,604 participants with established cardiovascular disease and overweight/obesity, without diabetes. Semaglutide 2.4 mg reduced the risk of major adverse cardiovascular events (MACE) by <strong>20%</strong> compared to placebo over a median follow-up of ~40 months. This was the first time an anti-obesity medication showed cardiovascular benefit in a dedicated outcomes trial (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37952131/">Lincoff et al., 2023</a>).</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== DOSING ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Dosing Schedule and Titration</h2>

<p>Semaglutide for weight management (Wegovy) follows a <strong>gradual titration</strong> to minimize gastrointestinal side effects. Rushing the titration is the most common mistake, and it leads to more nausea and higher dropout rates.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Weeks</th><th>Weekly Dose</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>1&ndash;4</strong></td><td>0.25 mg</td><td class="y">Starting dose; GI adjustment</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>5&ndash;8</strong></td><td>0.5 mg</td><td class="y">First escalation</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>9&ndash;12</strong></td><td>1.0 mg</td><td class="y">Most begin noticing weight loss</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>13&ndash;16</strong></td><td>1.7 mg</td><td class="y">Approaching maintenance</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>17+</strong></td><td>2.4 mg</td><td class="g">Maintenance dose</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>Each escalation step lasts 4 weeks. The full titration takes <strong>16 weeks</strong> to reach the maintenance dose of 2.4 mg.</p>

<p>The injection is administered <a href="/articles/how-to-inject-peptides-subcutaneously">subcutaneously</a> once weekly in the abdomen, thigh, or upper arm. The day of the week can be consistent but doesn't need to align with meals.</p>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--blue);">Practical Tips</h4>
    <p>If a dose is poorly tolerated, clinicians may extend the titration period (8 weeks at a given dose instead of 4) before escalating. Some patients achieve meaningful weight loss at 1.0 or 1.7 mg and may stay there if side effects are limiting.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--amber);">Missed Dose Protocol</h4>
    <p>If fewer than 5 days since the missed dose, take it as soon as possible. If 5 or more days have passed, skip it and resume on the next scheduled day. Don't double up.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ========== SIDE EFFECTS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Side Effects: What to Expect</h2>

<p>GI effects dominate, particularly during dose escalation. The good news: most people tolerate treatment long-term. In STEP 1, only <strong>7%</strong> of semaglutide participants discontinued due to adverse events vs. 3.1% on placebo.</p>

<h3>Common Side Effects (Over 10% Incidence)</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Side Effect</th><th>Incidence</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Nausea</strong></td><td class="r">44%</td><td>Most common; peaks during titration, improves over weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Diarrhea</strong></td><td class="r">30%</td><td>Usually mild to moderate</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Vomiting</strong></td><td class="y">24%</td><td>More common at higher doses</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Constipation</strong></td><td class="y">24%</td><td>Can alternate with diarrhea</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Abdominal pain</strong></td><td class="y">20%</td><td>Usually improves with time</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Less Common but Notable Risks</h3>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--amber);">Gallbladder Events</h4>
    <p>Cholelithiasis (gallstones) occurred at higher rates with semaglutide (~2.6% vs. 1.2% placebo). Rapid weight loss is an independent risk factor for gallstones regardless of the method used.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--amber);">Pancreatitis</h4>
    <p>Acute pancreatitis has been reported in GLP-1 RA users, though a causal link remains debated. In the STEP trials, events were rare and not statistically different from placebo. It remains a labeled warning.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--blue);">Increased Heart Rate</h4>
    <p>A small mean increase of 1&ndash;4 beats per minute has been observed. Clinical significance is unclear, but the SELECT trial's cardiovascular benefit is reassuring on this front.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--teal);">Hypoglycemia</h4>
    <p>Rare when used without sulfonylureas or insulin. Semaglutide's glucose-lowering effect is glucose-dependent, meaning it primarily acts when blood sugar is elevated.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="d-r">
  <div class="s">Boxed Warning: Thyroid C-Cell Tumors</div>
  <p>Semaglutide carries a boxed warning based on rodent studies showing dose-dependent thyroid C-cell tumors (medullary thyroid carcinoma). This hasn't been confirmed in humans, and the relevance is debated (rodent thyroid C-cells have far greater GLP-1 receptor density). However, semaglutide is <strong>contraindicated</strong> in patients with a personal or family history of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) or Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndrome type 2 (MEN 2).</p>
</div>

<h3>Muscle Loss Concerns</h3>

<p>Weight lost with semaglutide is approximately <strong>60&ndash;75% fat mass</strong> and <strong>25&ndash;40% lean mass</strong>. That's broadly consistent with the composition of weight loss seen with caloric restriction alone.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Practical Advice</div>
  <p>Resistance training and high protein intake (<strong>1.2&ndash;1.6 g/kg/day</strong>) are critical to preserve muscle while on semaglutide. Don't skip the weights.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== COMPARISON ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Semaglutide vs. Tirzepatide: Head-to-Head</h2>

<p><strong><a href="/articles/tirzepatide-complete-guide">Tirzepatide</a></strong> (Mounjaro for diabetes, Zepbound for weight management) is a dual GIP/GLP-1 receptor agonist. In cross-trial comparisons, tirzepatide has shown greater weight loss than semaglutide.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Semaglutide (Wegovy)</th><th>Tirzepatide (Zepbound)</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td><td>GLP-1 agonist (single)</td><td class="g">Dual GIP/GLP-1 agonist</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Max Weight Loss</strong></td><td>~15% (STEP 1, 68 wk)</td><td class="g">~22.5% (SURMOUNT-1, 72 wk)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>CV Outcomes Trial</strong></td><td class="g">SELECT: 20% MACE reduction</td><td class="y">Pending (SURPASS-CVOT)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>FDA Approval (Obesity)</strong></td><td>Jun 2021</td><td>Nov 2023</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Long-Term Safety Data</strong></td><td class="g">More extensive</td><td class="y">Less (newer drug)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>GI Side Effects</strong></td><td>Similar</td><td>Similar</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Cost</strong></td><td>~$1,300&ndash;$1,400/mo</td><td>~$1,000&ndash;$1,100/mo</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>The SURMOUNT-1 trial showed tirzepatide 15 mg produced mean weight loss of <strong>22.5%</strong> at 72 weeks (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35658024/">Jastreboff et al., 2022</a>). Cross-trial comparisons are imperfect (different populations, durations, endpoints), but the magnitude of difference is clinically meaningful.</p>

<div class="d-p">
  <div class="s">Choosing Between Them</div>
  <p>Tirzepatide is newer with less long-term safety data. GI side effects are broadly similar, and cost is comparable. The choice often comes down to availability, insurance coverage, and individual clinical response. Read our full <a href="/articles/semaglutide-vs-tirzepatide-comparison">semaglutide vs. tirzepatide comparison</a> for more detail.</p>
</div>

