<!-- ========== COMPOUNDING CONTROVERSY ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>The Compounding Controversy (2025&ndash;2026)</h2>

<p>Compounded semaglutide has been one of the most contentious regulatory issues in recent pharmaceutical history. Here's the timeline.</p>

<div class="cd ca">
  <div class="tg">Regulatory Timeline</div>
  <h3>How We Got Here</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:12px;"><strong>2022&ndash;2023:</strong> Severe Wegovy and Ozempic shortages placed semaglutide on the FDA's Drug Shortage List, which permits compounding pharmacies to produce copies of shortage-listed drugs under Section 503A and 503B.</p>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:12px;"><strong>2023&ndash;2024:</strong> Hundreds of compounding pharmacies and telehealth platforms began offering compounded semaglutide at a fraction of brand cost. The market grew rapidly.</p>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:12px;"><strong>October 2024:</strong> The FDA removed semaglutide from the shortage list, asserting that Novo Nordisk had resolved supply constraints. This triggered the legal basis for prohibiting compounding.</p>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;"><strong>2025&ndash;2026:</strong> Legal battles continue. Courts have issued mixed rulings, with some temporary injunctions allowing continued compounding. Some pharmacies have reformulated using semaglutide salt forms (e.g., semaglutide sodium), arguing these are distinct. The FDA disagrees.</p>
</div>

<div class="d-a">
  <div class="s">Current Status (February 2026)</div>
  <p>The legality of compounded semaglutide is actively contested. Patients using compounded products should be aware of the uncertain regulatory future, the lack of FDA oversight on compounded formulations (no standardized potency testing; sterility standards vary by pharmacy), and the potential for supply disruptions due to enforcement actions.</p>
</div>

<h3>Safety Concerns with Compounded Products</h3>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--red);">Risks</h4>
    <p>Compounded injectables carry inherent sterility and potency risks. Several adverse events have been reported to the FDA. Dosing accuracy varies between pharmacies. No requirement for clinical trials or bioequivalence testing.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--teal);">Counterpoint</h4>
    <p>503B outsourcing facilities operate under cGMP (current Good Manufacturing Practices) and FDA inspection, providing a higher standard than traditional 503A pharmacies. Not all compounders are equal.</p>
  </div>
</div>

